{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Scientists and Indian advocates are questioning why the government is not acting more quickly on a cleanup.", "abstract": "Hundreds of abandoned uranium mines, some contaminated with radioactivity, dot 27,000 square miles of Navajo territory in Arizona, Utah and New Mexico, and are the legacy of shoddy mining practices and federal neglect; mines supplied critical materials to the nation's nuclear weapons program from the 1940s through the 1980s; scientists and Indian advocates are questioning why the government is not acting more quickly on a cleanup.", "section_name": "U.S.", "print_page": "18", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Leslie", "role": "reported", "lastname": "MACMILLAN", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By LESLIE MACMILLAN", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/01/us/uranium-mines-dot-navajo-land-neglected-and-still-perilous.html", "lead_paragraph": "Scientists and Indian advocates are questioning why the government is not acting more quickly on a cleanup.", "headline": {"main": "Uranium Mines Dot Navajo Land, Neglected and Still Perilous", "print_headline": "Uranium Mines Dot Navajo Land, Neglected and Still Perilous"}, "_id": "53f53ec838f0d87ef470e1c5", "word_count": "1581", "multimedia": [{"height": 366, "url": "images/2012/04/01/us/URANIUM-1/URANIUM-1-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2012/04/01/us/URANIUM-1/URANIUM-1-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "366"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2012/04/01/us/URANIUM-1/URANIUM-1-thumbStandard.jpg", "legacy": {"thumbnail": "images/2012/04/01/us/URANIUM-1/URANIUM-1-thumbStandard.jpg", "thumbnailwidth": "75", "thumbnailheight": "75"}, "subtype": "thumbnail", "width": 75, "type": "image"}], "pub_date": "2012-04-01T00:00:00Z", "source": "The New York Times", "news_desk": "National", "keywords": [{"value": "Navajo In